<LENGTH>
<P>
305 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
EUROPEAN REVERIE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BARBARA THORNBURG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The rich patina of age glows from the rooms of designer Linda Chase's home. 
Wrought-iron Gothic-revival torchiers stand in front of terra-cotta-colored 
silk draperies bound with 19th-Century gold cords. 
</P>
<P>
An Old Master painting hovers over three clay putti standing atop a 
18th-Century hand-painted Italian desk. It's an environment so steeped in the 
textures of the past that a colleague of Chase, seeing a photo of one of the 
rooms, asked which European country the house was in. He was startled to learn 
that he was looking at Chase's recently restored 1927 home in the Hollywood 
Hills. 
</P>
<P>
Purchased a year-and-a-half ago, the house once belonged to a Canadian opera 
singer. "There was an existing fairy-tale quality to the house with its 
medieval weather vane, turreted roof line and small-paned windows: I just 
enhanced that magical quality," Chase explains. Letting the bones of the house 
guide her, she left it as undisturbed as possible. The woodwork remained 
untouched except for a lone living-room beam that was beyond repair: She 
painted it parchment and then embellished it with hand-painted cartouches. The 
major face lift for the house came in the multilayered paint scheme: It's the 
layers of paint that give the walls depth and opalescence. The living room, for 
example, takes its color from a parchment base diluted with an Italianate blue 
then tinted with three additional ochre glazes. 
</P>
<P>
Against that backdrop, she's arranged an inspired collection of genuine 
antiques and reproductions. "I mix all kinds of things if I feel the effect is 
right," explains Chase, who works with clients worldwide and wrote the recently 
released book "In the Romantic Style." Armfuls of cut flowers and candles 
create a peaceful reverie -- "a world," Chase says, "that's in a different 
point in time." BARBARA THORNBURG 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Above: Chase's frequent travels to Europe turned up wrought-iron 
Gothic torchiers, purchased at a London auction; 19th-Century gold cords, found 
in a small antique shop in Paris, and a neoclassical daybed hand painted blue 
with gold leaf, discovered in Rome. Underneath them all -- an 18th-Century 
Aubusson.; Photo, COLOR, Top right: Old Master painting floats over 
18th-Century Italian desk.; Photo, COLOR, Bottom: Italian clay putto 
representing spring stands next to French bouillotte lamp with tole shade -- 
both 18th Century -- and 50-year-old reproduction Etruscan vase. Antique French 
scene de marionette (puppet-show stage) hangs on wall. David Phelps 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
