<HEADLINE>
<P>
CINEFILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KIRK HONEYCUTT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Roy Scheider, Julian Sands and Michael Zelniker join Judy Davis and Peter 
Weller in David Cronenberg's film of William Burroughs' novel, "Naked Lunch." 
Shooting begins January in Toronto and Morocco. Jeremy Thomas and Gabriella 
Martinelli will produce for the Recorded Picture Co. 
</P>
<P>
Kurtwood Smith joins Madonna in Mainline Productions' "Boxing Helena," a 
psychological thriller about obsessive love to be directed by Jennifer Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
Jeffrey Jones has been cast in "Welcome to Buzzsaw," Interscope's dark comedy 
starring Matthew Broderick. French filmmaker Francis Veber will direct the 
screenplay by Joshua and Daniel Goldin starting Jan. 2 in Santa Cruz. Universal 
will distribute the film, produced by Robert Cort and Karen Murphy. 
</P>
<P>
George Segal and bandleader Jack Sheldon join Bette Midler and James Caan in 
Fox's "For the Boys," the episodic tale of a USO singer which Midler, Bonnie 
Bruckheimer and Margaret South are producing from Marshall Brickman and Neal 
Jimenez's script. Mark Rydell directs in L.A. early January. 
</P>
<P>
"Kate &amp; Allie's" Ari Meyers joins Ed O'Neill, JoBeth Williams and Ethan 
Randall in Fox's "Dutch," a John Hughes production, which is now shooting in 
L.A. and will later move to Chicago. Peter Faiman directs Hughes' script about 
an estranged father and son who must travel cross-country. 
</P>
<P>
Another cross-country trip takes place when Drew Barrymore, Meat Loaf, Vince 
Edwards and Michael J. Pollard star in Planet Productions' "Motorama," a 
10-year-old boy's adventures tooling around in a 1966 Mustang. The film gets 
under way this week in Arizona under the direction of Barry Shils . 
</P>
<P>
Alyssa Milano of "Who's the Boss," Jonathan Silverman and George Newbern star 
in Creative Edge Films' collegiate comedy "Co-Ed," written and directed by 
Jimmy Zeilinger. The Martin Wiley-Jeffrey Neuman produced film is shooting in 
L.A. 
</P>
<P>
Kenny Ortega will choreograph and direct Disney's "Newsies," a musical about a 
New York newspaper strike in the late 19th Century. Producer Michael Finnell 
hopes to launch production the end of March. 
</P>
<P>
Martin Lawrence from New Line Cinema's "House Party" and Darryl Sivad head the 
cast in New Line's "Talking Dirty After Dark," written and directed by Topper 
Carew. The film is now shooting in L.A. 
</P>
<P>
Jack Warden joins John Ritter in Imagine Films/Universal's "Problem Child II," 
scheduled to get under way next month. 
</P>
<P>
James Marshall ("Twin Peaks") and Cuba Gooding (currently starring in 
Columbia's "Boyz N the Hood") are set to star in Columbia's "Bare Knuckles" 
They play high-school kids caught up in an illegal boxing and betting 
organization. Steve Roth will produce and Rowdy Herrington direct a script by 
Lyle Kessler ("Orphans"), which has been rewritten by Nick Kazan ("Reversal of 
Fortune"). Shooting begins in Chicago Jan. 15. 
</P>
<P>
There'll be more bare knuckles when Don Wilson, the light heavyweight 
kick-boxing champion of the world, stars for producer Paul Maslak in Unifilm 
International's martial- arts thriller, "Ultimate Weapon," next May in Miami. 
KIRK HONEYCUTT 
</P>
