<P>
TIES THAT BIND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Supervisor John MacDonald made a rather incredible admission at the board 
meeting Dec. 4 when he stated he had previously made a commitment not to site a 
landfill at Merriam Mountain while he was a member of the Oceanside City 
Council in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
This admission calls into question the integrity of the selection process. 
</P>
<P>
Are there other sites that were rejected, not because they were inappropriate, 
but because of undisclosed political commitments previously made? 
</P>
<P>
Shouldn't Supervisor MacDonald now disqualify himself from any discussion of 
the Merriam Mountain sites in the upcoming months? 
</P>
<P>
Has Supervisor MacDonald's previously unknown commitment caused him to continue 
to consider the Aspen Road site rather than look at a potentially more 
appropriate site because of a political deal? 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL A. PORTIGAL, Temecula 
</P>
</TEXT>
